It's the major legislative victory, assuming all goes well with those two votes, of his time in office thus far.

647
01:02:41,363 --> 01:02:49,692
The defeated candidate in presidential elections in Honduras, Salvador Nasralla, has accepted an invitation for talks with President Juan Orlando Hernandez.

648
01:02:50,213 --> 01:02:57,421
Mr Nasralla has accused his rival of rigging the vote and says he has handed evidence to the Organization of American States in Washington.

649
01:02:57,901 --> 01:02:59,343
He's demanding a new election.

650
01:03:00,664 --> 01:03:07,672
A bus carrying foreign tourists to Mayan ruins in Mexico has crashed, killing at least 12 people, including a child.

651
01:03:08,232 --> 01:03:12,757
The bus had been travelling to the eastern tip of the Yucatan Peninsula when it veered off the road.

652
01:03:13,197 --> 01:03:15,420
Here's our Mexico correspondent, Will Grant.

653
01:03:15,960 --> 01:03:27,252
The tourists had arrived in Mexico on board a Royal Caribbean cruise ship, and this, a visit to the beautiful Mayan ruins of Chacho Ben, was meant to be a pleasurable day trip to see a little of the country.

654
01:03:27,713 --> 01:03:35,922
However, a dozen people were killed and many more injured when the bus overturned on the highway out to the ruins, south of the popular resort of Tulum.

655
01:03:36,422 --> 01:03:39,448
An investigation is underway as to the cause of the crash.

656
01:03:39,869 --> 01:03:48,324
Many of the coastal roads in that particular state of Quintana Roo are poor and potholed, especially on the southern road down to the border with Belize.

657
01:03:49,140 --> 01:03:59,069
The US ambassador to the United Nations has said a missile fired at the Saudi Arabian capital Riyadh from Yemen bears the hallmarks of an attack using weapons provided by Iran.

658
01:03:59,690 --> 01:04:04,214
Houthi rebels, who are supported by Iran, claimed responsibility for the missile launch.

659
01:04:04,855 --> 01:04:09,840
The US ambassador, Nikki Haley, said she was very concerned about this latest development.

660
01:04:10,480 --> 01:04:18,804
According to the Houthis themselves, it was targeted at a meeting of Saudi leaders in Riyadh, in an area crowded with government offices.

661
01:04:19,624 --> 01:04:23,586
Thankfully, the missile was intercepted before it could hit its intended target.

662
01:04:24,246 --> 01:04:29,568
But the very fact of this attack is a flashing red siren for this council.

663
01:04:30,149 --> 01:04:34,951
It is only a matter of time before one of these missiles hits the target.

664
01:04:35,871 --> 01:04:37,472
World News from the BBC.

665
01:04:39,107 --> 01:04:45,470
The United Nations Refugee Agency has said it's stepping up its operation on the border between Cameroon and Southeast Nigeria.

666
01:04:46,050 --> 01:04:54,274
Thousands of Cameroonians have fled from their country after clashes between security forces and pro-independence groups in Cameroon's English-speaking region.

667
01:04:54,934 --> 01:05:01,917
Tensions between the English-speaking minority and the government, which is dominated by Francophones, have escalated in the last year.

668
01:05:03,366 --> 01:05:11,808
Canada and the United States have announced that they'll co-host a summit of foreign ministers to discuss the deepening crisis over North Korea's nuclear ambitions.

669
01:05:12,489 --> 01:05:15,809
The Canadian Foreign Minister, Chrystia Freeland, and the visiting U.S.

670
01:05:15,829 --> 01:05:21,871
Secretary of State, Rex Tillerson, said the meeting next month would include envoys from Japan and South Korea.

671
01:05:22,451 --> 01:05:27,233
It will consider how to improve the effectiveness of the current pressure campaign against Pyongyang.

672
01:05:28,867 --> 01:05:35,850
After forming a coalition with a far-right party, Austria's new chancellor has travelled to Brussels to reassure EU leaders.

673
01:05:36,351 --> 01:05:43,734
Sebastian Kurz, who leads the Conservative People's Party, has entered an alliance with the Eurosceptic and anti-immigration Freedom Party.

674
01:05:44,354 --> 01:05:51,538
Speaking in Brussels at a news conference with the President of the European Commission, Mr Kurz said his government remained a committed EU member.

675
01:05:55,279 --> 01:05:58,121
We want to contribute to a strong European Union.

676
01:05:58,621 --> 01:06:09,685
We would like a European Union which will be stronger when it comes to the big issues and at the same time stands back when it comes to smaller issues, where member states or regions are well equipped to make decisions.

677
01:06:10,366 --> 01:06:15,488
I do appreciate that over the past few years there's been an effort to reduce legislative initiatives.

678
01:06:16,468 --> 01:06:24,570
An investigation has been launched in India after a metro train crashed through the walls of a station in the capital Delhi during a trial run.

679
01:06:25,190 --> 01:06:30,491
The incident took place just days ahead of the planned inauguration of the new line by the Prime Minister.

680
01:06:31,052 --> 01:06:32,572
There were no passengers on the train.

681
01:06:33,212 --> 01:06:35,293
Trains on the new line are planned to be driverless.

682
01:06:36,253 --> 01:06:37,133
BBC News

683
01:06:43,671 --> 01:06:44,332
Hello, welcome.

684
01:06:44,412 --> 01:06:45,953
This is Business Matters.

685
01:06:46,033 --> 01:06:47,955
Fergus Nicol with you today from London.

686
01:06:48,116 --> 01:06:51,979
In a moment, our main headline after a year of legislative frustration.

687
01:06:52,580 --> 01:06:56,304
President Trump secures a win in the House of Representatives, at least.

688
01:06:56,384 --> 01:07:00,888
Republicans pushing through the most radical overhaul of the US tax system in decades.

689
01:07:00,908 --> 01:07:02,410
We'll talk about that in a second.

690
01:07:02,810 --> 01:07:07,135
Later in the program, why is China setting up a carbon market?

691
01:07:07,575 --> 01:07:21,224
It's a commitment to put this system into place, which puts on notice the rest of the world, especially existing carbon markets in the European Union and California, that there will be potential to link up with the China's market, and that's a very big deal.

692
01:07:21,544 --> 01:07:25,027
Does China's involvement mean it's an idea that is really catching on?

693
01:07:25,067 --> 01:07:26,067
Let's greet our guests.

694
01:07:26,107 --> 01:07:28,569
We'll be talking about these and other issues during the hour.

695
01:07:28,989 --> 01:07:32,792
From New Delhi this morning, Madhavan Narayanan of FirstPost.com.

696
01:07:32,812 --> 01:07:34,373
Madhavan, good to have you back with us.

697
01:07:34,413 --> 01:07:36,374
Thanks for starting the day with business matters.

698
01:07:36,594 --> 01:07:37,555
Thank you, Fergus.

699
01:07:37,835 --> 01:07:38,796
Greetings from Delhi.

700
01:07:39,096 --> 01:07:40,717
Greetings from London.

701
01:07:40,737 --> 01:07:42,399
Let's say hello from Austin, Texas.

702
01:07:42,879 --> 01:07:45,981
Andy Euler, reporter with Marketplace on American Public Media.

703
01:07:46,262 --> 01:07:51,886
We'll be hearing your account of tax issues in Texas in just a couple of minutes.

704
01:07:51,906 --> 01:07:52,587
You're most welcome.

705
01:07:53,318 --> 01:07:54,618
Thanks for having me Fergus, good to be here.

706
01:07:54,778 --> 01:07:55,619
Good to have you back.

707
01:07:55,679 --> 01:08:02,300
We'll start then of course in the US where the administration could be forgiven for thinking tonight one down, one to go.

708
01:08:02,320 --> 01:08:13,043
The Republican majority in the House of Representatives successfully steered its tax reform bill through to a 227 to 203 vote victory.

709
01:08:13,563 --> 01:08:15,303
Next comes the Senate.

710
01:08:15,343 --> 01:08:17,644
There's been a bit of a kerfuffle as we heard in the news.

711
01:08:18,044 --> 01:08:22,725
The Senate sent the bill back to the House to think it can get another vote tomorrow morning and then the Senate gets its

712
01:08:23,225 --> 01:08:25,748
go, probably before the end of Wednesday.

713
01:08:25,848 --> 01:08:32,655
And if that goes according to plan, the first legislative win of Donald Trump's presidency will go to his desk for signature.

714
01:08:33,376 --> 01:08:37,019
And we can expect that to be done with something more than his customary flourish.

715
01:08:37,440 --> 01:08:38,281
Back to the House then.

716
01:08:38,441 --> 01:08:39,242
What happened today?

717
01:08:39,262 --> 01:08:41,644
A completely partisan outcome.

718
01:08:42,024 --> 01:08:43,246
Here's the Speaker, Paul Ryan.

719
01:08:43,835 --> 01:08:52,159
We said in 2016 that it would take real tax reform for families and businesses to get the American economy growing, and we were serious.

720
01:08:52,639 --> 01:08:56,241
On January 1, Americans are going to wake up with a new tax code.

721
01:08:56,581 --> 01:08:59,983
In February, they're going to see withholdings go down so they see bigger paychecks.

722
01:09:00,463 --> 01:09:05,766
And April 15 will be the last day they have to comply with the old, bad system.

723
01:09:06,026 --> 01:09:07,587
This is a good day for America.

724
01:09:07,847 --> 01:09:09,207
This is a good day for workers.

725
01:09:09,507 --> 01:09:12,469
This is a great day for growth, and we're very excited about this moment.

726
01:09:12,897 --> 01:09:15,965
Minority leader Nancy Pelosi, not so much.

727
01:09:16,306 --> 01:09:21,178
She highlighted poll numbers, which have shown a steady decline in public support for the tax plan.

728
01:09:21,762 --> 01:09:26,386
Outside the Congress, the American people have already made their decision.

729
01:09:26,966 --> 01:09:32,410
Polling shows that Americans oppose the GOP tax scam by a margin of two to one.

730
01:09:32,950 --> 01:09:39,495
Hardworking families see right through the brazen con job Republicans are trying to sell them.

731
01:09:40,016 --> 01:09:44,619
So why aren't our Republican colleagues standing with their constituents?

732
01:09:45,119 --> 01:09:49,583
Why aren't they joining us, insisting on a better deal for American families?

733
01:09:50,224 --> 01:09:56,268
away from the beltway, how is this highly charged issue playing out in the places where the real taxpayers live?

734
01:09:56,768 --> 01:10:01,411
I've been talking to two Republican voters in Missouri.

735
01:10:01,531 --> 01:10:03,072
Walt Cooper lives in Kansas City.

736
01:10:03,453 --> 01:10:06,895
He's retired, but he used to work in the medical services technology sector.

737
01:10:07,435 --> 01:10:09,857
Janet Matteliati is an attorney in St.

738
01:10:09,897 --> 01:10:10,137
Louis.

739
01:10:11,068 --> 01:10:16,310
I think it's hopefully going to be good for most of the people in the United States.

740
01:10:16,691 --> 01:10:19,992
I think simplifying things will be particularly good.

741
01:10:20,012 --> 01:10:30,757
I know some people say that this is only going to be good for the rich, but I think it will help people across the board and a lot of the middle class, of which I consider myself part of the middle class.

742
01:10:31,341 --> 01:10:33,442
Opening thoughts from Walt Cooper then.

743
01:10:33,622 --> 01:10:42,965
Just tell us how you see what's been going on in Washington and how well it reflects your concerns about the tax system as it's operated through your professional life.

744
01:10:43,625 --> 01:10:48,147
I agree with Janet somewhat that I think it's going to be a positive thing.

745
01:10:48,467 --> 01:11:00,991
I'm just recently retired and so I've been around a while and have watched taxes come and go, raise and lower, and I think giving people back as much money as you can and leaving it in the people's hands

746
01:11:01,491 --> 01:11:03,032
is the best way to go about this.

747
01:11:03,232 --> 01:11:07,795
Government tends to waste our money at times, and they always want more.

748
01:11:08,376 --> 01:11:14,860
And so I believe that if we do get some meaningful tax relief, I think it's going to be positive for our economy.

749
01:11:15,100 --> 01:11:26,727
So when we heard Speaker Ryan say on Capitol Hill earlier on Tuesday, this is giving the money back to the people, you're all for that because you think the government doesn't spend it right?

750
01:11:26,967 --> 01:11:30,049
Well, I mean, I don't know of any government that spends it right.

751
01:11:30,129 --> 01:11:40,615
And I think we have so many examples of government continuing to, I mean, they're one of the largest employers in the United States, and they've never cut back on anything ever, as far as I can remember.

752
01:11:40,996 --> 01:11:50,962
And really, this is not, I mean, it's a tax cut, but it's a little bit of a misnomer in my mind, because they continue to talk about deficit that it'll create.

753
01:11:51,462 --> 01:11:54,964
and continue conversations about paying for the tax cut.

754
01:11:55,064 --> 01:12:02,229
So when you use the term paying for the tax cut, to me, that's code for, well, the government needs just as much money as they always did.

755
01:12:02,389 --> 01:12:15,937
So what I would really like to see is not only a tax cut, but the government being forced to tighten their belt to say, we're going to give people back some of their money, and the government itself is going to run on less.

756
01:12:16,097 --> 01:12:17,838
I agree with Walt that I think the

757
01:12:18,338 --> 01:12:21,660
government doesn't spend our money wisely in many cases.

758
01:12:21,680 --> 01:12:29,186
I know certain things have to be taken care of, but just like any family here in America, when things are tight, you have to tighten your belt and rein things in.

759
01:12:29,266 --> 01:12:32,768
And I agree with Walt that I don't think the federal government ever does that.

760
01:12:32,848 --> 01:12:34,729
We just seem to increase and increase.

761
01:12:34,909 --> 01:12:40,513
So I would certainly like this followed up with spending cuts and things so that we can pay for it.

762
01:12:40,573 --> 01:12:42,755
Now, one of my hopes is that in

763
01:12:43,354 --> 01:12:56,471
reducing the corporate rate that we can get more businesses back in the United States, since our rates were higher than most other countries, which will help the economy and will help pay for some of this, but I do think we need to do some spending cuts also.

764
01:12:57,044 --> 01:13:05,452
Janet, I want to stay with you first and pick up a word you used I think is going to resonate with a lot of listeners in the U.S., and that is simplifying.

765
01:13:05,972 --> 01:13:14,720
Thank the Lord I don't have to deal with the IRS, but I have American friends who do, and even the kind of briefing paper to help you do your taxes

766
01:13:15,220 --> 01:13:17,381
requires a doctorate, I think, to understand.

767
01:13:18,061 --> 01:13:27,905
Tell us about the complexity of regular tax paying and how much harder it gets maybe when you're dealing with wills and all kinds of complicated legal procedures.

768
01:13:28,726 --> 01:13:33,888
I mean, it's very complicated and I would have to laugh as an attorney who does estate tax planning.

769
01:13:34,401 --> 01:13:42,006
I don't even do my own income tax returns, because there's all kinds of regulations for that, in addition to the stuff that I deal with.

770
01:13:42,086 --> 01:13:51,892
But I think they're on the right track as far as reducing a lot of the itemized deduction and increasing the standard deduction, because that's going to help a lot of people.

771
01:13:51,932 --> 01:13:55,875
I think a lot more people will do the standardized deductions as opposed to the itemized.

772
01:13:56,075 --> 01:14:04,542
As it relates to my business, one part of the tax plan doubles the exemption from the state taxes and gift taxes.

773
01:14:04,682 --> 01:14:08,405
So by doing that, a lot of our clients will fall within that.

774
01:14:08,445 --> 01:14:21,575
So it's going to reduce what they have to do in some advanced planning, as far as the state tax would be concerned, and allows them to go back to do some more capital gains type planning with their estate plan, since they don't have to worry about the federal estate tax.

775
01:14:23,817 --> 01:14:26,077
The word onerous just comes to my mind.

776
01:14:26,478 --> 01:14:32,160
I have a certified public accountant that's been doing my taxes for 30 years because I'm afraid to do them myself.

777
01:14:32,440 --> 01:14:44,545
If you are in my stage of life where you're retiring and you're thinking about how you're going to live the rest of your life and live well as best you can on the money you have, one of the things that CPAs will tell you is,

778
01:14:44,925 --> 01:14:46,847
you'd better be planning for taxes.

779
01:14:46,907 --> 01:14:49,009
But how does the average person do that?

780
01:14:49,149 --> 01:14:54,194
There's entire industries in the United States to manage people's taxes.

781
01:14:54,475 --> 01:15:00,461
So, I mean, that's all you kind of need to know, is it's so complicated that there isn't anybody that knows it all.

782
01:15:00,781 --> 01:15:04,184
I think simplification is a wonderful concept.

783
01:15:04,325 --> 01:15:06,607
I hope that it is, in fact, real.

784
01:15:06,907 --> 01:15:08,548
I know this is a huge document.

785
01:15:08,789 --> 01:15:22,700
I wonder whether you can highlight, each of you, maybe three things that you think are immediately going to help America in terms of boosting jobs, boosting business, boosting collective incomes.

786
01:15:23,482 --> 01:15:23,862
Sure.

787
01:15:23,962 --> 01:15:33,668
I think I maybe kind of mentioned it before, but I think the reduction in the corporate tax will help to get some businesses back in the United States.

788
01:15:34,028 --> 01:15:44,414
One thing, and it really doesn't have to do with taxes, but I am in favor of the drilling in Alaska, and I think that will help our economy and help us become more oil independent.

789
01:15:44,614 --> 01:15:52,318
And again, I'm just hoping that reducing the rates is going to get more money in average Americans' pockets, and then they will in turn be spending that.

790
01:15:52,598 --> 01:15:53,138
That's three.

791
01:15:53,318 --> 01:15:56,719
Walt, you're definitely allowed to agree.

792
01:15:56,879 --> 01:16:09,343
Well, I think that Janet mentioned this earlier, but in terms of simplification, doubling the standard deduction for the average person, about 30 percent, I think, of American itemized deductions.

793
01:16:09,403 --> 01:16:11,324
So that means 70 percent don't.

794
01:16:11,404 --> 01:16:16,345
So when you double that, that immediately puts money back in that middle class pocket.

795
01:16:16,605 --> 01:16:26,968
And I think that if you go back to the days of Ronald Reagan and moving into the Clinton administration, we've seen what putting money back in people's pockets does for the economy.

796
01:16:27,048 --> 01:16:42,131
So we might get a double whammy with that and the corporate tax rate that I agree that Janet talked about, because there's going to be a lot of repatriation of money coming back in the United States from corporations in here who have that money parked overseas.

797
01:16:42,251 --> 01:16:44,252
I think our economy is going to be hot for a while.

798
01:16:44,809 --> 01:16:45,770
hot for a while.

799
01:16:45,891 --> 01:16:48,815
Our thanks to Walt Cooper and Janet Matteliani.

800
01:16:48,855 --> 01:16:50,757
They're both speaking to us from Missouri.

801
01:16:51,078 --> 01:16:57,226
And let's go to Andy now in Austin, because you've been out and about talking to voters in rural parts of Texas.

802
01:16:57,246 --> 01:17:00,471
Tell us a little bit about where you've been and the kind of people we're going to hear from.

803
01:17:00,958 --> 01:17:01,479
That's right.

804
01:17:01,679 --> 01:17:04,521
I went outside of Austin, which is right in the center.

805
01:17:04,601 --> 01:17:09,205
It's the capital of Texas, and I went about an hour west to a town.

806
01:17:09,846 --> 01:17:16,351
It was actually Burnett and Llano counties, and I went to Horseshoe Bay, which is kind of a retirement community.

807
01:17:18,113 --> 01:17:23,298
It's mostly sort of upper middle class folks, and they move out there from the hill country.

808
01:17:23,318 --> 01:17:24,659
A lot of folks have land out there.

809
01:17:25,620 --> 01:17:46,977
But, I really kind of just wanted to get a sense from them, I mean, the counties that I went to were 75% Trump voters, so I wanted to get a sense from them, sort of, what they were thinking about this tax bill, and just really honest, visceral reactions from, you know, not even necessarily the intricacies of the bill, because it's, like you said, 600 pages, and, you know, a lot of senators haven't read it.

810
01:17:47,697 --> 01:17:52,962
I just wanted from these folks to get a real visceral reaction to what this tax bill meant to them.

811
01:17:53,833 --> 01:17:54,974
My name is Leon Fuller.

812
01:17:55,315 --> 01:17:57,697
I work at Horseshoe Bay Veterinarian Clinic.

813
01:17:58,037 --> 01:17:59,699
He's got faith in the tax bill.

814
01:17:59,899 --> 01:18:08,027
You know, I hope it does pass, and I hope we do get some money back to the middle class, which is all it's going to do is turn around and make our economy stronger.

815
01:18:08,307 --> 01:18:12,130
Retired marketing and sales rep Frank Hosia is a little more cautious.

816
01:18:12,711 --> 01:18:13,392
It's way too early.

817
01:18:14,092 --> 01:18:18,814
Between the Senate and Congress, they're going to have so many different reiterations of this.

818
01:18:19,454 --> 01:18:22,375
So anything we think about that we know, don't.

819
01:18:22,795 --> 01:18:25,136
But he does think the tax system needs an overhaul.

820
01:18:25,456 --> 01:18:28,277
He voted for Trump and thinks the bet on trickle-down is a good one.

821
01:18:28,658 --> 01:18:32,899
Having the highest corporate tax rate in the world makes no sense.

822
01:18:33,539 --> 01:18:37,761
We're seeing the amount of jobs that are leaving the country and have been leaving the country.

823
01:18:38,341 --> 01:18:42,743
Let's figure out how to bring the monies back to the country as well as the jobs back to the country.

824
01:18:43,163 --> 01:18:48,029
Just a couple miles down the road in another little town, Marble Falls, I stop in at the R Bar.

825
01:18:48,609 --> 01:18:49,590
I'm Nadine Rader.

826
01:18:49,650 --> 01:18:53,134
I'm from Marble Falls and I'm a server at Noon Spoon Cafe.

827
01:18:53,515 --> 01:18:53,655
I'm 25.

828
01:18:54,476 --> 01:18:56,798
She didn't vote in last year's presidential election.

829
01:18:57,099 --> 01:19:02,285
I'm a single mom of two, so I'll get two child credits back at the end of the year.

830
01:19:02,925 --> 01:19:04,585
And that's not going up for me.

831
01:19:04,685 --> 01:19:16,628
But as far as somebody who, let's say, is making $150,000 in the home, they're going to get more money back than me, who is below $20,000 a year, just barely making it with two kids, single moms.

832
01:19:16,728 --> 01:19:20,689
So I mean, yes, they are putting in more money into the system.

833
01:19:20,709 --> 01:19:22,290
But no, it's not helping me.

834
01:19:22,530 --> 01:19:25,831
Across the street is Bill's Burgers, where Roland Parker is grabbing a beer.

835
01:19:26,251 --> 01:19:27,811
He's a self-employed cabinetmaker.

836
01:19:28,191 --> 01:19:30,352
He also didn't vote in the presidential election.

837
01:21:09,713 --> 01:21:15,597
It's certainly a big win, but certainly at the same time, Trump seems to be late to the party.

838
01:21:15,617 --> 01:21:21,301
You know, the interest rate hikes have begun, increases have begun, inflation is low, employment is up.

839
01:21:21,822 --> 01:21:30,668
Therefore, what Trump is offering is not some kind of a fixing of the problem, but more like an icing on the cake.

840
01:21:30,708 --> 01:21:34,751
He might like to tweet about it, but the problem doesn't need fixing anymore.

841
01:21:35,411 --> 01:21:49,186
But on the other hand, there are issues related to whether there is a demand in the economy to revive capital, because as of now, last night's report suggested some industries may not really gain, whereas some others will.

842
01:21:49,567 --> 01:21:55,914
And looking at a higher perspective, the real threats to jobs haven't gone away yet.

843
01:21:56,354 --> 01:22:00,299
You know, the middle class may get money back, but what about the Rust Belt?

844
01:22:01,781 --> 01:22:05,926
You know, there are robots, robotics coming in, there is 3D printing.

845
01:22:06,466 --> 01:22:12,053
These are technological issues that can't be simply solved by a silver bullet like a tax plan.

846
01:22:12,333 --> 01:22:15,675
I want to ask, can I just ask you a quick comparison question?

847
01:22:15,715 --> 01:22:16,976
In fact, it comes in two parts.

848
01:22:17,156 --> 01:22:24,481
One is about the bureaucracy and the complications of filing for the IRS, which we heard about from Janet a moment ago.

849
01:22:24,501 --> 01:22:28,604
So let's do that bit first and tell me how that plays out in India.

850
01:22:28,624 --> 01:22:29,785
Then I'll get on to the other thing.

851
01:22:30,225 --> 01:22:33,208
Well, India is much more bureaucratic.

852
01:22:33,268 --> 01:22:34,910
In fact, India, the problem is opposite.

853
01:22:34,950 --> 01:22:53,587
India has a very low tax-to-GDP ratio, and the government has been trying to make its own India's biggest tax reform in the past several decades by introducing what's called the goods and services tax, a single one for the entire nation, which the Prime Minister called a good and simple tax, but small businesses do not find it good or

854
01:22:53,927 --> 01:23:11,604
simple because it increases the complexities of filing electronic returns 13 times a year, some reliefs have been given, it's been a toing and froing between the government and the opposition and some of the tax rates are as high as 28% and apart from that there is this whole cumbersome, you know, things like

855
01:23:12,745 --> 01:23:14,867
eBay bills and papers you have to maintain.

856
01:23:15,247 --> 01:23:18,089
So nobody's liking the complexity or the tax rate.

857
01:23:18,389 --> 01:23:26,014
And it was an election issue that the Prime Minister's BJP managed to somehow beat in this week's elections, last week's elections.

858
01:23:26,754 --> 01:23:36,500
And to that extent, the government is safe, but it's quite shaken by some of these tax initiatives, which it says will benefit India in the long run.

859
01:23:36,601 --> 01:23:38,302
But, you know, no one's really seen the long run.

860
01:23:39,122 --> 01:23:42,264
OK, we'll come back to this in the second half of the programme.

861
01:23:42,365 --> 01:23:42,925
Thanks both.

862
01:23:43,085 --> 01:23:44,206
Andy, hold fire.

863
01:23:44,226 --> 01:23:46,908
I know you've got a lot more to say about this.

864
01:23:46,928 --> 01:23:52,052
I want to look into some other news now here on business matters.

865
01:23:52,072 --> 01:23:53,092
We're going to go to Spain.

866
01:23:53,112 --> 01:23:58,096
The northern region of Catalonia has seen a lot of campaigning in the last few weeks.

867
01:23:58,296 --> 01:24:03,480
The election called by Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy happens on Thursday.

868
01:24:03,960 --> 01:24:06,001
Now, you'll remember we covered it on this programme.

869
01:24:06,281 --> 01:24:12,623
Catalonia's attempt to break away from Spain in the wake of that disputed referendum unleashed a real political storm.

870
01:24:13,143 --> 01:24:17,165
The former president of the regions is still in exile in Belgium.

871
01:24:17,465 --> 01:24:19,606
A lot of his colleagues are in prison.

872
01:24:19,986 --> 01:24:23,967
And the Spanish government has introduced direct rule across Catalonia.

873
01:24:24,328 --> 01:24:27,749
Let's hear now from the BBC's Guy Hedgcoe in Barcelona.

874
01:24:29,547 --> 01:24:34,488
I'm on the Ramblas, the boulevard in central Barcelona that's such a magnet for tourists.

875
01:24:35,409 --> 01:24:39,050
Barcelona receives around 17 million tourists each year.

876
01:24:39,690 --> 01:24:47,592
But in October, tourist arrivals fell by 5 percent, a dip which has been attributed to the political turmoil here during that month.

877
01:24:48,492 --> 01:24:55,674
In addition, around 3,000 companies have moved their legal base out of Catalonia to other parts of Spain recently.

878
01:24:56,134 --> 01:25:01,576
The firm Help My Cash, which compares financial services, is one of those that made the move.

879
01:25:01,916 --> 01:25:03,797
Laurent Amar is its founder.

880
01:25:04,437 --> 01:25:07,338
In September, we were in a very uncertain environment.

881
01:25:07,418 --> 01:25:12,820
We were not able to clearly say what was going to happen, so we had to move the

882
01:25:13,480 --> 01:25:16,102
legal headquarter out of Catalonia.

883
01:25:16,302 --> 01:25:21,044
We have one of our shareholders who lives in Madrid so it made sense to be there.

884
01:25:21,224 --> 01:25:26,467
Mr. Amar says the economic impact of the political instability was easy to gauge.

885
01:25:27,348 --> 01:25:33,371
What we saw was a huge spike in traffic from people who were looking for where to put your money.

886
01:25:33,731 --> 01:25:34,852
From one day to the other,

887
01:25:35,452 --> 01:25:47,887
The number of users who were concerned about bank account exploded and the number of people who were looking for mortgages shrank because basically the whole mortgage business in Catalonia froze.

888
01:25:48,328 --> 01:25:55,016
And so since October we've seen a drastic reduction in the number of people who come and look for mortgages in Catalonia.

889
01:25:56,632 --> 01:26:00,993
Politically, Catalonia is much calmer now than it was just a few weeks ago.

890
01:26:01,473 --> 01:26:11,315
And certainly, it does look pretty much like business as usual, even though you can still see quite a few pro-independence flags hanging from balconies of apartments.

891
01:26:12,156 --> 01:26:16,917
But there are concerns that the effects for the economy could still be felt for some time.

892
01:26:17,537 --> 01:26:26,299
I'm in the commercial district of central Barcelona, where Carlos Ribadulla, a businessman who has been very critical of the independence movement, has his offices.

893
01:26:27,079 --> 01:26:32,402
Since September, October, November, we've been experiencing here in Catalonia a very dramatic economic turmoil.

894
01:26:32,702 --> 01:26:45,949
For instance, we've seen consumption going down, where in the rest of Spain it's going up about 20% for restaurants, 25% for cinemas and shows, 25% for big department stores.

895
01:26:46,129 --> 01:26:50,752
Are these elections going to solve the crisis, calm down the turmoil, do you think?

896
01:26:51,512 --> 01:26:52,913
Sure, at least they might.

897
01:26:52,994 --> 01:26:59,380
We have a choice, we have an option, I mean, an opportunity on December the 21st with the coming elections.

898
01:26:59,540 --> 01:27:09,409
If we have a clear majority of pro-unity, pro-constitutional parties, yes, we'll have more stability, confidence and trust will be regained.

899
01:27:13,153 --> 01:27:19,119
But polls suggest that pro-independence parties could win more seats than the unionists in the election.

900
01:27:19,739 --> 01:27:29,829
This campaign advert featuring deposed Catalan president Carles Puigdemont speaking from exile in Belgium presents the vote as another referendum on the independence issue.

901
01:27:31,130 --> 01:27:35,712
Ernest Maragall is a candidate for the pro-independence Catalan Republican Left Party.

902
01:27:36,392 --> 01:27:45,216
He says that if Madrid agreed to engage in negotiations about the territorial issue, the political and economic situation would improve dramatically.

903
01:27:45,656 --> 01:27:52,259
If we had just normal dialogue at the table, the social and economic effects would disappear immediately.

904
01:27:52,419 --> 01:27:58,522
Imagine now, after the election of the 21st of December, the Spanish state would accept

905
01:27:59,102 --> 01:28:02,063
that the best way is a real dialogue with Catalonia.

906
01:28:02,243 --> 01:28:09,125
Then it would have an immediate and spectacular effect in terms of calming all the instability.

907
01:28:09,265 --> 01:28:16,347
But the Spanish government looks unlikely to engage in talks with Catalonia's pro-independence forces anytime soon.

908
01:28:17,667 --> 01:28:27,910
Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy insists that he will continue to defend the unity of Spain against those who want to break away.

909
01:28:28,983 --> 01:28:39,932
Although pro-independence parties might win the election, they could fall short of a majority, in which case it could be up to a coalition of left-leaning parties to decide who governs.

910
01:28:41,913 --> 01:28:50,720
The full results of the election will be known on the same day that the annual Christmas lottery is held in Spain, and with tickets on sale in the street.

911
01:28:51,721 --> 01:28:56,384
But this election, called by Mr Rajoy, might be his biggest gamble yet.

912
01:29:00,420 --> 01:29:03,001
Guy Hedgcoe reporting from Barcelona.

913
01:29:03,041 --> 01:29:09,684
Of course, from Thursday on, we'll be bringing you results of that election in Catalonia here at the BBC World Service.

914
01:29:10,105 --> 01:29:13,266
Much more to come on this edition of Business Matters.

915
01:29:13,646 --> 01:29:16,608
Before the end of the hour, we're going to be talking about the ownership

916
01:29:17,068 --> 01:29:37,435
of the Carolina Panthers, why an NFL franchise is political, it's got race politics in it as well, there's the hashtag MeToo debate involved, it's stirring up a lot of contemporary American themes in one big package, and there is a lot of money at stake.

917
01:29:41,096 --> 01:29:42,857
This is the BBC World Service.

