01:30:55,479 --> 01:31:01,485
From Oregon, we'll meet the Zebra entrepreneurs, business people of a different stripe.

933
01:31:01,746 --> 01:31:03,748
And Diddy bids for the Panthers.

934
01:31:04,248 --> 01:31:07,652
Will he become the NFL's first black franchise owner?

935
01:31:11,587 --> 01:31:13,348
BBC News with Marion Marshall.

936
01:31:13,789 --> 01:31:16,731
US senators are debating the Trump administration's tax bill.

937
01:31:17,252 --> 01:31:23,277
The House of Representatives earlier approved the bill that would see the biggest overhaul of the country's tax system in decades.

938
01:31:23,937 --> 01:31:30,443
If the legislation passes in the Senate, it'll have to be sent back to the House for another vote because of a last-minute procedural glitch.

939
01:31:31,550 --> 01:31:41,062
The defeated candidate in the fiercely disputed presidential elections in Honduras, Salvador Nasralla, has accepted an invitation for talks with the president, Juan Orlando Hernandez.

940
01:31:41,643 --> 01:31:46,409
Mr Nasralla has accused his rival of rigging the vote and says he's taped evidence of this.

941
01:31:47,711 --> 01:31:57,040
Twelve people have been killed in the Yucatan Peninsula in Mexico, when a bus carrying foreign tourists to see Mayan ruins veered off the road and toppled over.

942
01:31:57,581 --> 01:32:02,426
Eighteen passengers were injured and have been taken to hospital, but they're said to be in a stable condition.

943
01:32:03,785 --> 01:32:12,438
Canada and the United States will co-host a summit of foreign ministers to discuss the effectiveness of current measures to curb North Korea's nuclear ambitions.

944
01:32:13,039 --> 01:32:17,726
The meeting in Vancouver next month will include envoys from Japan and South Korea.

945
01:32:19,087 --> 01:32:19,447
The U.S.

946
01:32:19,507 --> 01:32:28,953
ambassador to the United Nations, Nikki Haley, has said a missile fired at the Saudi capital, Riyadh, bears the hallmarks of an attack using weapons provided by Iran.

947
01:32:29,533 --> 01:32:34,195
The Saudi military shot down the missile, which Houthi rebels in Yemen say they launched.

948
01:32:35,296 --> 01:32:43,360
China has unveiled plans for a nationwide carbon market, allowing companies to trade permissions to emit greenhouse gases within an overall cap.

949
01:32:43,981 --> 01:32:46,582
The carbon market will cover the emissions of about 1,700 energy companies.

950
01:32:49,160 --> 01:32:55,243
Austria's new chancellor has travelled to Brussels to reassure EU leaders that his government is committed to the bloc.

951
01:32:55,843 --> 01:33:05,867
Sebastian Kurz, who leads the Conservative People's Party, has entered an alliance with the Eurosceptic and Anti-Immigration Freedom Party, sparking alarm in Brussels.

952
01:33:07,428 --> 01:33:08,348
BBC News.

953
01:33:16,047 --> 01:33:16,928
Hello, welcome back.

954
01:33:17,048 --> 01:33:19,150
Business Matters with Fergus Nicol.

955
01:33:19,510 --> 01:33:27,598
And now China has unveiled plans to set up a national carbon market in a bid to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.

956
01:33:28,219 --> 01:33:33,704
This market would bring about a quarter of the world's emissions under some kind of trading system.

957
01:33:34,104 --> 01:33:37,708
Zhang Yong is the vice chairman of the National Development and Reform Commission.

958
01:33:38,128 --> 01:33:40,511
He says the trading will be based in Shanghai.

959
01:33:41,171 --> 01:33:44,553
It will involve more than 1,700 power companies.

960
01:33:45,373 --> 01:33:53,197
Paula de Perna is an environmental analyst who helped set up the pilot scheme on behalf of the Chinese government that led to this announcement.

961
01:33:53,497 --> 01:33:55,418
She's been talking to my colleague Tim Franks.

962
01:33:56,229 --> 01:34:06,813
The Chinese system will be covering the power sector, which is, of course, the source of a lot of emissions, and will have an impact not only on the reduction of emissions, but also on the cost of energy.

963
01:34:07,013 --> 01:34:23,199
What's critical about today's announcement is that it's a commitment to put this system into place, which puts on notice the rest of the world, especially existing carbon markets in the European Union and California, that there will be potential to link up with the Chinese market, and that's a very big deal.

964
01:34:23,499 --> 01:34:26,663
The potential for linkage establishes an international language.

965
01:34:26,723 --> 01:34:39,299
If you think of a carbon ton, if you think of an emissions allowance as a new form of currency, as an international translation of environmental science from science to finance, that's really what's exciting about all this.

966
01:34:39,839 --> 01:34:46,223
I think the Chinese entry into this new world of commodities trading requires them to play by the rules.

967
01:34:46,403 --> 01:34:54,227
And so if they were to try to game such a system, which is under such an international microscope, it would be a very significant national embarrassment.

968
01:34:54,268 --> 01:34:58,170
Now, that doesn't mean there won't be mistakes and there won't be probably some cheating.

969
01:34:58,210 --> 01:35:03,553
But I think overall, it's a step into best practice at the financial services level.

970
01:35:03,933 --> 01:35:11,855
And given how major an emitter of carbon China is, what sort of impact do you think this could have globally?

971
01:35:12,115 --> 01:35:15,656
Well, I think it could have transformational impact in numerous ways.

972
01:35:15,716 --> 01:35:19,337
First of all, the obvious, most important one is to actually reduce the emissions.

973
01:35:19,437 --> 01:35:27,238
So if the Chinese power sector becomes comfortable with the rules and begins to understand it, they could get into it big time and they like to trade.

974
01:35:27,299 --> 01:35:32,640
And so it could become quite significant that they're playing an internal competition game of who can reduce quickest.

975
01:35:32,960 --> 01:35:33,700
And then secondly,

976
01:35:34,300 --> 01:35:38,122
all companies that operate in China use power in one way or another.

977
01:35:38,202 --> 01:35:44,144
So if the power sector is coming under control of the cap and trade, the users of power will feel the impact.

978
01:35:44,424 --> 01:35:52,347
So it means that American companies, European companies, any company in China will feel the effects of this cap and trade indirectly.

979
01:35:52,547 --> 01:35:57,329
And that can be good because you can never have too much efficiency when it comes to energy use.

980
01:35:57,429 --> 01:36:00,730
So if the system works as it can, it could be very significant.

981
01:36:01,907 --> 01:36:03,768
Thanks to Paula de Perna.

982
01:36:04,088 --> 01:36:06,348
A transformational impact then.

983
01:36:06,388 --> 01:36:13,471
Let me reintroduce from New Delhi this morning, Madhavan Narayanan of FirstPost.com, Andy Euler of Marketplace in Austin.

984
01:36:13,491 --> 01:36:20,973
I don't suppose you want to step in here, Andy, with a crystal clear definition of what this involves, because, you know, people have been talking about this for a long time.

985
01:36:21,013 --> 01:36:25,495
I remember going to Brazil, oh God, must be 10, 12 years ago, people talking about it.

986
01:36:25,515 --> 01:36:29,416
It just hasn't caught on at the scale that the Green Movement hoped it would.

987
01:36:29,916 --> 01:36:34,579
Well, and what stuck with me, too, was what Paula DiPerna said right at the end.

988
01:36:34,600 --> 01:36:42,906
She said, if this market works, which is really important, because there are three things that this carbon market needs.

989
01:36:43,006 --> 01:36:47,369
It has to know how much carbon is being emitted and where it's coming from.

990
01:36:48,610 --> 01:36:55,515
You need to have some sort of registry to figure out where it is coming from and who to hold accountable for that.

991
01:36:57,215 --> 01:37:03,598
And then you also have to think about how much this carbon is going to cost.

992
01:37:03,618 --> 01:37:05,579
You have to have sort of a market for it.

993
01:37:05,979 --> 01:37:08,240
And none of these things right now exist.

994
01:37:08,260 --> 01:37:12,361
I mean, the idea that China's going to come in and set up this carbon market is great.

995
01:37:12,621 --> 01:37:14,122
I agree with her.

996
01:37:14,182 --> 01:37:15,362
I think this is a great thing.

997
01:37:15,402 --> 01:37:16,663
But at the same time,

998
01:37:17,243 --> 01:37:22,566
This is going to have a long, long rollout process, because we're going to have to figure out all of the other things.

999
01:37:22,926 --> 01:37:24,907
You can say, all right, this carpet market's open.

1000
01:37:24,927 --> 01:37:27,328
Now we've got to figure out how we're actually going to do it.

1001
01:37:27,349 --> 01:37:31,591
Do you buy the premise, Madhavan, of this conceptually?

1002
01:37:32,810 --> 01:37:42,695
Yes, I do, except that look at the challenges in trying to buy something out of someone for something that person didn't do.

1003
01:37:43,055 --> 01:37:45,376
That's what carbon emissions trading is all about.

1004
01:37:45,416 --> 01:37:47,917
So it's like buying a vacuum sort of a thing.

1005
01:37:47,937 --> 01:37:49,738
You know, I didn't do this, so pay me for it.

1006
01:37:49,818 --> 01:37:51,539
It's a bit of a ransom thing, if you ask me.

1007
01:37:52,039 --> 01:38:03,590
But there's also the irony that we're talking more of bitcoins than carbon trading, whereas carbon trading is actually producing social and ecological value.

1008
01:38:03,811 --> 01:38:07,935
Yeah, I was wondering whether carbon trading would ever become as sexy as bitcoin trading.

1009
01:38:08,495 --> 01:38:19,877
Yeah, there is a case to make it sexy, but as Andy said, you know, we need to have policing mechanisms to ensure that somebody is actually reducing emissions and therefore is worth paying for that.

1010
01:38:20,277 --> 01:38:27,298
India took baby steps around circa 2008 to list and authorize certain companies to do it.

1011
01:38:27,758 --> 01:38:35,600
But, you know, the global economic crisis and the collapse of Lehman Brothers took our attention away from climate change towards Wall Street.

1012
01:38:36,500 --> 01:38:36,640
of the

1013
01:38:52,032 --> 01:38:54,374
some incentives out of carbon trading on the one hand.

1014
01:38:54,434 --> 01:38:59,958
On the other hand, you have alternatives in form of everything from electric cars to solar energy to switch over.

1015
01:39:00,398 --> 01:39:08,244
This is a glorious dawn, if I may say so, for what I call green pricing or greenomics.

1016
01:39:08,824 --> 01:39:12,127
And I do hope the governments move faster on this.

1017
01:39:12,427 --> 01:39:15,209
My belief is that no government is moving fast enough on this.

1018
01:39:15,489 --> 01:39:39,150
And Andy, probably the good news about this with China's involvement, as we're hearing from Paul, it sets an example that the others can buy into and indeed tie into, but it also perhaps stops richer countries kind of effectively buying out their guilt by attributing it to somebody else, playing a market in a fairly cavalier way and buying themselves out of these kind of caps.

1019
01:39:39,590 --> 01:39:48,239
Well, and it's also this idea that China is now going to be, perhaps, the global leader in reducing carbon emissions.

1020
01:39:48,299 --> 01:39:52,403
I mean, the United States, it doesn't feel like that's a priority here.

1021
01:39:52,463 --> 01:40:00,691
From everybody that you talk to, everybody that you're hearing politically, it doesn't feel like carbon emissions is one of the things that we talk about.

1022
01:40:00,731 --> 01:40:01,772
I mean, we spent

1023
01:40:02,112 --> 01:40:04,374
the whole first half of the show talking about tax reform.

1024
01:40:04,955 --> 01:40:06,676
We're not talking about global warming.

1025
01:40:06,696 --> 01:40:07,837
We're not talking about climate change.

1026
01:40:07,857 --> 01:40:09,178
We're not talking about carbon emissions.

1027
01:40:09,699 --> 01:40:25,032
And so if China's going to step in and be the global leader, I hope, from what it appears to me, that other rich countries are going to pay attention and say, you know what, if there's a market for this, of course, the American says, if there's a market for this, we're going to get in on it.

1028
01:40:25,553 --> 01:40:28,135
Because if there is that carbon market, of course America's going to get in on it.

1029
01:40:28,595 --> 01:40:33,800
Hold the thought about Bitcoin, by the way, folks, because we're coming back to that before the end of the half hour.

