1032
01:40:37,283 --> 01:40:43,048
Now, if you're running a startup in America and you're looking for investment, it helps if you're a man.

1033
01:40:43,268 --> 01:40:49,353
Between 2011 and 2013, $51 billion of venture capital poured into U.S.

1034
01:40:49,413 --> 01:40:54,778
companies, but only 3% of that went to companies led by a female CEO.

1035
01:40:55,298 --> 01:40:58,661
Findings published, by the way, in the journal Venture Capital.

1036
01:40:59,101 --> 01:41:04,845
If you're female and you're from an ethnic minority, well, then the prospects of raising money get even bleaker.

1037
01:41:05,085 --> 01:41:08,828
But now a group of entrepreneurs in Silicon Valley is trying to do something about it.

1038
01:41:09,248 --> 01:41:15,053
The BBC's Riga Morris went along to the first meeting of so-called zebras in Portland, Oregon.

1039
01:41:16,065 --> 01:41:18,426
Zebras fix what unicorns break.

1040
01:41:19,086 --> 01:41:22,267
That's the motto of a movement in Silicon Valley's tech industry.

1041
01:41:23,048 --> 01:41:27,269
It may sound like marketing nonsense, but the movement is dead serious.

1042
01:41:27,890 --> 01:41:34,112
The zebras are frustrated by what they see as a lust for so-called unicorn companies.

1043
01:41:34,632 --> 01:41:36,753
Right now, unicorns is a popular

1044
01:41:37,293 --> 01:41:42,818
title for companies that are valued at over a billion dollars, and Silicon Valley is chasing after these.

1045
01:41:42,838 --> 01:41:49,925
You know, there aren't a ton in existence, but they're enough to make people kind of gold rush hungry for finding the next unicorn company.

1046
01:41:50,005 --> 01:41:51,186
That's Jennifer Brandel.

1047
01:41:51,226 --> 01:41:57,231
She's one of the founders of the Zebra Movement, which aims to change the way tech startups are funded.

1048
01:41:57,992 --> 01:42:07,839
It's very hard to find investors who aren't thinking about striking it rich, especially because now with technology, companies can scale very quickly sometimes, sometimes too quickly for their own good.

1049
01:42:08,920 --> 01:42:10,441
And so zebras are an alternative.

1050
01:42:10,481 --> 01:42:18,126
Instead of a unicorn, which is mythical and rarely seen, zebras are actually real and they get their competitive advantage from cooperating.

1051
01:42:18,306 --> 01:42:27,033
Unicorns, I think, are dangerous in that they grow up so quickly and before they've had a chance to really understand the power that they wield and how to do it responsibly.

1052
01:42:30,174 --> 01:42:33,956
I went to the zebras first ever gathering, DazzleCon.

1053
01:42:38,317 --> 01:42:43,039
It's called DazzleCon because a group of zebras is known as a dazzle.

1054
01:42:43,579 --> 01:42:43,980
It's true.

1055
01:42:44,000 --> 01:42:44,960
I looked it up.

1056
01:42:46,098 --> 01:42:49,220
But this isn't your standard Silicon Valley tech conference.

1057
01:42:49,340 --> 01:42:51,802
First of all, the guests are predominantly women.

1058
01:42:52,463 --> 01:42:57,907
And secondly, the chat isn't the standard Silicon Valley grow fast or die trying.

1059
01:42:58,848 --> 01:43:07,694
At DazzleCon, they're talking about social impact, sustainability, and about how women receive less than 10% of all venture capital funding in Silicon Valley.

1060
01:43:07,714 --> 01:43:09,295
Thank you so much.

1061
01:43:09,315 --> 01:43:15,340
Ania Williams joined the Zebra movement as a co-founder after struggling to raise money for her wearable tech company, Tinsel.

1062
01:43:15,740 --> 01:43:20,725
I pitched over 100 investors and at the end of the day I ended up landing two.

1063
01:43:21,706 --> 01:43:26,631
And I realized that there were a lot of issues with the way that the VC model works.

1064
01:43:26,731 --> 01:43:28,313
I think that the model is very broken.

1065
01:43:28,353 --> 01:43:34,539
I think that obviously it favors a specific type of person over everyone else.

1066
01:43:34,820 --> 01:43:36,522
Do you mean white male?

1067
01:43:36,862 --> 01:43:38,504
Well, you know, you said it.

1068
01:43:40,104 --> 01:43:41,585
One of the zebras is Tara Reid.

1069
01:43:41,865 --> 01:43:43,705
She's the founder of Apps Without Code.

1070
01:43:44,526 --> 01:43:49,828
She says the zebra movement is important, but that it could only exist in the tech industry.

1071
01:43:50,068 --> 01:43:54,009
This distinction between zebras and unicorns, this is only a tech conversation.

1072
01:43:54,370 --> 01:43:58,851
If you have conversations with any other industry, right, what you want to be is a zebra.

1073
01:43:58,891 --> 01:43:59,492
That's normal.

1074
01:43:59,532 --> 01:44:00,732
That's how businesses work.

1075
01:44:01,112 --> 01:44:05,554
For some reason in tech, we have this different idea of how business works, right?

1076
01:44:05,874 --> 01:44:10,117
Well, it's because we have these fairy tales of boys in their dorm rooms becoming billionaires.

1077
01:44:10,177 --> 01:44:21,786
Right, but I think if you hear the fairy tales in other industries, like the fairy tale is Pepsi or Coca-Cola, the fairy tale is some other business that generates profit and distributes that profit.

1078
01:44:21,926 --> 01:44:23,227
Those are the different fairy tales.

1079
01:44:23,467 --> 01:44:27,691
So I think outside of Silicon Valley, this is, of course, it's normal.

1080
01:44:27,751 --> 01:44:33,195
So I think the zebra movement will mainly exist in Silicon Valley because that's what the rest of the world is doing.

1081
01:44:34,250 --> 01:44:38,694
That's the BBC's Riga Morris meeting members of the Zebra Gathering.

1082
01:44:38,714 --> 01:44:41,216
It happened in Portland, Oregon.

1083
01:44:41,457 --> 01:44:45,080
DazzleCon 2017 was the title.

1084
01:44:45,220 --> 01:44:47,302
What's the collective noun for unicorns?

1085
01:44:47,882 --> 01:44:50,365
At Fergus Nicol, if you know the answer.

1086
01:44:50,645 --> 01:44:52,406
Madhavan, would this work in India?

1087
01:44:52,687 --> 01:44:53,688
Do you buy that concept?

1088
01:44:54,564 --> 01:45:10,679
Well, I just heard an interesting story last week about a venture capital meeting that took place in Delhi in which an investor bluntly told a woman that he will not invest in a company founded by a lady who would take six months off for maternity.

1089
01:45:11,180 --> 01:45:14,023
So basically we are looking at asking

1090
01:45:14,843 --> 01:45:17,625
bungee jumpers to help a blind woman cross the road.

1091
01:45:17,705 --> 01:45:26,309
I mean, to draw an analogy between, you know, this is about greed and scale and value and as, you know, it could be a very white male thing, but this is about capitalism.

1092
01:45:26,829 --> 01:45:28,230
So zebra is a great idea.

1093
01:45:28,250 --> 01:45:34,133
First of all, it creates a wonderful zebra versus unicorn debate to raise awareness on this issue.

1094
01:45:34,693 --> 01:45:42,461
But I have a feeling that the answers do not lie in conventional venture capital, but probably in three other things that are already there.

1095
01:45:42,841 --> 01:45:44,883
One is boutique investments.

1096
01:45:45,384 --> 01:45:52,331
The other is impact investment, which is an offshoot of venture capital that looks at social goals rather than economic scaling.

1097
01:45:52,811 --> 01:45:54,893
And the third would be philanthropy.

1098
01:45:55,233 --> 01:46:04,901
You know, there's a lot of money going on in philanthropy and some of those funds could be put into helping minorities and women and entrepreneurs of a different kind so that they can co-exist.

1099
01:46:05,281 --> 01:46:08,364
You know, one of the Silicon Valley's favorite word is ecosystem.

1100
01:46:08,904 --> 01:46:21,792
Maybe there isn't category for an ecosystem, but having said that, let me joke that in this whole zebra thing, everything is not in black and white, there are grey areas, and the zebras will have to earn their stripes.

1101
01:46:23,093 --> 01:46:25,694
Okay, pile them in, pile them in.

1102
01:46:25,954 --> 01:46:26,855
That's very interesting.

1103
01:46:26,955 --> 01:46:29,196
I like the point about social entrepreneurship.

1104
01:46:29,236 --> 01:46:32,198
That's something we can do in more detail, I think, on this program in the future.

1105
01:46:32,218 --> 01:46:33,119
That's a great point.

1106
01:46:33,659 --> 01:46:35,221
to make a marker.

1107
01:46:35,321 --> 01:46:46,795
Andy, we heard there from the women talking to Reagan in Silicon Valley itself and that thing going on in Portland, that this is something they're focused on their area.

1108
01:46:47,136 --> 01:46:48,518
Can it translate across America?

1109
01:46:49,218 --> 01:47:11,682
I don't know because it still feels like, I mean, you talk to, we have a technology reporter, a tech reporter, Molly Wood, who talks about, she spends a lot, I mean, she lives in San Francisco and spends a lot of time in Silicon Valley and talks about sort of the ecosystem, like we were talking about, being basically a lot like the priesthood, a lot, very male and a lot of white males.

1110
01:47:12,462 --> 01:47:17,903
And so when you get into these meetings, so many female entrepreneurs are getting into these meetings.

1111
01:47:19,643 --> 01:47:25,025
They're not being listened to or they're just being told no.

1112
01:47:25,085 --> 01:47:28,186
Is that Silicon Valley or is that the VC sector?

1113
01:47:29,727 --> 01:47:34,048
It feels like it is sort of the VC sector and it feels like so much of that money

1114
01:47:35,149 --> 01:47:41,094
is with a certain set of people who invest in other people that look like them.

1115
01:47:41,114 --> 01:47:45,258
I mean, you know, it's sort of the idea of shuffling that money around.

1116
01:47:45,858 --> 01:47:56,528
It doesn't feel like Silicon Valley is much different from other places in the United States where there's a ton of money and there's a ton of really powerful people that are shuffling that money around.

